result.execSummary:
The defendant Kennyth Leroy Aubol Jr. was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Take (<=$500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
11:09 AM Defendant Kennyth Leroy Aubol Jr. in court.  Attorney Peter James Marvin Kruger in court for State of Wisconsin. State recites that for Count 1 and 2 a withheld sentence for 1 year probation. Conditions to include comply with programming as deemed necessary by the DOC and pay a $50 fine plus costs in each count. State has complied with Victim's Rights. Defendant states probation was not part of agreement from prior hearing. Court reviews prior recommendation of the State at last hearing. Defendant plead guilty to Count 1 and 2 on October 18, 2022.

Court imposes $50 fine plus costs on count 1 and count 2. Court reviews DNA to be taken. Defendant believes that is on file but will stop at jail with form provided. Court signs DNA form.

1:34 PM Defendant Kennyth Leroy Aubol Jr. in court.  Attorney Peter James Marvin Kruger in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls case. Court notes matter is being recorded as commissioner is out. Defendant has reviewed complaint. 
Court recites charges against defendant and possible penalties. Defendant pleads guilty to Count 1. Defendant pleads guilty to Count 2. Court informs defendant of rights given up by their plea. Court finds factual basis. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been freely, voluntarily and intelligently made.  Court finds Defendant understands all the rights they are waiving by their plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is entered.
State recites priors. State recommends $50 on each count, no jail, no credit, plus costs. Asks for adjournment for separate sentencing to notify victims. Court sets dates. 
State requests $1500 signature bond, conditions of no contact with Walmart stores.
No objection.
Court orders $500 signature bond, no contact with Walmart.
Sentencing hearing scheduled for October 28, 2022 at 11:00 am.
